        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity: The current SED modeling of FL Cha suggests a disk mass of ~6 Jupiter masses and an extent of at least 100AU. Cieza et al. (2013) give a continuum flux at 870 microns of 30 mJy which, for the requested beam size of 0.12 arcsec and the object spatial extent, imply a specific flux of at most 0.5 mJy/beam, mainly driven by the degeneracies in the SED fitting procedure. To assure a 3-sigma detection we then need a 1-sigma rms sensitivity of 0.1 mJy. With this rms we are sensitive to ~10 Earth masses for the total continuum bandwidth of 4 GHz, and at a distance of 160 pc. This setup translates into ~45 mins of ALMA time, including calibration and overheads. With the requested continuum sensitivity we are able to probe the dynamics of gas too. Because we can minimize the cloud contamination by measuring 13CO(3-2) and CO(3-2) lines, we can obtain a sensitivity of 12 mJy per channel for a 0.3 km/s channel width. These lines are proven to be strong in protoplanetary disks, which is not always the case for the other lines that lie in the Band 7 frequency range.

Correlator setup: We decided to include two spectral windows for continuum measurements. We set a bandwidth of 2 GHz per spectral window, with a spacing of 31 MHz. For the line setup we decided to configure the LO to have a minimum channel spacing of ~0.2 km/s in a 234 MHz bandwidth spectral window. We binned the spectral resolution by a factor of 4 to reduce the data rate and to not over-sample the lines.

Antenna setup: Our main science goal is to resolve the continuum disk structure, particularly the cavity size and shape which is not strongly constrained by the current fitting. As shown in Fig.3, left panel, the most extended configuration (i.e. C34-7) ensures that we will resolve the hole. This configuration makes the shadowing a negligible problem because of the long distances between antennas, even for the low altitude of the Chamaleonis molecular cloud (dec ~-77 deg).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
